body: Comment ‚ÄúSCHOOL‚Äù...  ‚Ä¶ and I will send you the link to a mini guide on how to start homeschooling (as someone who had NO CLUE what she was doing). This includes‚Ä¶   ¬∑ The different types of homeschool methods (classical, traditional, eclectic, virtual, etc.)  ¬∑ The best homeschool curriculums by subject  ¬∑ The best books to read if you‚Äôre looking to get started  ¬∑ What to consider before you start homeschooling  I can‚Äôt believe we finished ONE YEAR OF HOMESCHOOLING! If you would have told me I would have four kids AND that I would be homeschooling them, I would have been shocked. But the more I think about it, the more sense it makes.  If you‚Äôre on the fence about whether or not to homeschool my best advice is this: there is no ‚Äúright‚Äù decision; there is only the right decision for YOU.  Don‚Äôt listen to what other people say; don‚Äôt be scared of what people might think - just consider why you‚Äôre having these ideas about wanting to homeschool in the first place, and that will lead you to your answer.  Our year was certainly NOT perfect. It wasn‚Äôt a solution for EVERYTHING. But, it was a solution for most of the things that I hoped it would be. Namely, I got more time back with my kids and as a family, it slowed things down, life felt more quality and less quantity, we had more flexibility, and I actually felt like they learned A TON.   There is a new wave of homeschooling kids and parents and I‚Äôm totally here for it!  Will we homeschool next year? That is the plan. Will we homeschool forever? I don‚Äôt know. I honestly see a lot of benefits in sending your kids to school. At the same time, I see LOTS of benefits to homeschooling. It is really about what is best for the kids and the parents in that window of life, which is why we are taking it a year at a time.
author: brookeraybould

body: Comment ‚ÄúBEACH‚Äù ‚Ä¶  ‚Ä¶. To get the link to our 30A rental home called ‚ÄúAnchors Away‚Äù and use code ‚ÄúBROOKE‚Äù to get $200 off when booking! ‚òÄÔ∏è  The rental is a 3 bed / 3 bath with one king room, one queen room, and a huge bunk room with four queen size bunks (where our boys stay!). The home is located in the heart of Seacrest Beach (between Rosemary Beach and Alys Beach) at the end of a safe culdesac. This is our sixth time traveling to 30A and our fourth year staying at Anchors Away 30A in Seacrest Beach. We HIGHLY recommend it! It feels like home away from home.   But first, what is 30A?  The Observer says, ‚Äú30A is actually a county road on the Emerald Coast of the Florida Panhandle, which boasts a series of small, unique beach towns, including Seaside, Alys Beach and Rosemary Beach. Think of 30A is the Southeast‚Äôs answer to the Hamptons.‚Äù  One of those beach towns called ‚ÄúSeaside‚Äù was the location where the movie, The Truman Show, was filmed - if you want a feel for the picturesque vibe! body: üìù Comment ‚ÄúPLAN‚Äù for the link to our weekly activity and meal plan template. üìö Comment ‚ÄúSCHOOL‚Äù for the link to all homeschool info (free!). ‚è∞ Comment ‚ÄúMORNING‚Äù to learn how to create an early morning routine.  I can‚Äôt believe we have almost finished ONE YEAR (our very FIRST year) of homeschool. ü§Øüëèüèª  For those of you who don‚Äôt know (or are new here), we made the decision to homeschool our boys for the first time a few weeks before the academic school year started.  I had them enrolled in a Catholic school that - all things considered - we loved. But, something intuitively felt wrong about having them gone all day at school and the stress of life that came with having to follow the school schedule and formalities.  **I fully understand that school works for many kids and families!  It just wasn‚Äôt working for us during this stage of family life.  There is no one really close to me that homeschools their kids and I never had any sort of allegiance to the idea. The idea and decision came as a solution to a problem I had been wanting to fix.  For those who follow my IG stories, you know how scared I was to make this decision, how much I doubted myself, and how many times I said I probably wasn‚Äôt going to do it.  And then, I did.  And now? We have almost finished ONE YEAR of school at home.  This message is for the mom, who has an idea on her heart, but doesn‚Äôt know how to make it a reality or is too scared to pull the trigger for whatever reason. Trust that little voice inside of you that nags and whispers, and if it whispers for long enough, my encouragement is to GO FOR IT.  You can do hard things - and you were made to step in the direction of your calling. üôåüèª  As for homeschool, we will be homeschooling the big boys again next year. Woo! The littles will be starting Kinder and Pre School in ‚Äúregular‚Äù school to build a foundation (that is the plan at the moment), then after Kinder I will cycle them into homeschool.   As always, one year at a time! ‚ô•Ô∏è

body: Comment ‚ÄúMINDSET‚Äù...  ‚Ä¶ and I‚Äôll send you a free download on how I think about motherhood and the approach I take!  James Clear has a quote that I love and often refer back to, ‚ÄúOne of the most effective things you can do to build better habits is to join a culture where your desired behavior is the normal behavior. New habits seem achievable when you see others doing them every day. If you are surrounded by fit people it‚Äôs easier to exercise regularly. If you are surrounded by musicians, it‚Äôs easier to practice your instrument.‚Äù  When it came to motherhood culture, I felt this. I guess I didn‚Äôt want to be part of the norm. After a few years in, I realized the environment I had created - starting with the content I consumed - was only holding me back.  What I wanted to create for myself, instead, was an environment that helped me become a better mom and person. That included friend groups, books read, and content consumed.  Malcom Gladwell says that we become an expert after we reach 10,000 hours of deliberate practice. Therefore, if I was/am a stay-at-home mom working 8 hour days, that would mean that I would be an expert in my field as a mom when my first child reached the age of 3.4 years old.  I understand that kids growing into different ages and changes, and adding new kids into the mix might increase this range of expertise. But, by and large, I should know what I‚Äôm doing in a handful of years.  Then, at what rate should I develop above what I consider to be baseline motherhood? And, how can I be better than I was yesterday?  I threw relatable mom content out the window. I didn‚Äôt want to be relatable; I wanted to be good - really good - at what I devoted my life to doing. Being a person and being a mom.  I‚Äôm not saying that relatable content doesn‚Äôt have its place. What I‚Äôm saying is that if you consider your media consumption like the food pyramid - I want ‚Äúrelatable/entertaining‚Äù to be at the top next to junk food. And I want ‚Äúeducational / self-development‚Äù to be at the bulk base. When I changed this, my life drastically improved.
author: brookeraybould

body: Whatever your version of Super Mom is‚Ä¶ do you, boo. üí™üèª  üëâüèªComment ‚ÄúPLAN‚Äù to get our Sunday planning download and ‚ÄúMORNING‚Äù to learn how to create a morning routine of your own!   For me? I didn‚Äôt know that having kids would force two very different sides of me. At times, the bad side and the very best side. It‚Äôs almost as if our children shine a light on the things we need to work on and give us an opportunity to rise up to the challenge of life. If we pay close enough attention we can be the kind of person we always hoped we‚Äôd be - because of them.   In early motherhood, my one goal was to keep up. That‚Äôs it. But then I had three then four kids, and the lifestyle I was living just wasn‚Äôt conducive to keeping up. Throw in an at-home business and homeschool and there is no way I‚Äôd be able to function the way I do and keep things straight if I didn‚Äôt change my life completely.  And so, it did. I thank my kids for bringing out this side of me that I always wanted to be, but couldn‚Äôt become on my own.  I always knew that alcohol (personally) wasn‚Äôt a positive part of my life - now it is a rarity that I drink. I knew that I had boundless energy after a workout - now I made the habit to workout daily. I knew that books helped my mind and soul - now it‚Äôs a part of my everyday life. I knew that there was a way to make our weeks flow better - now we plan it all out on Sundays.  Our kids will challenge us every day of our lives and it presents an opportunity to get creative with solutions. Instead of feeling guilty for falling short, perhaps we can have a little more faith in our abilities to get it right.  You‚Äôre capable and you‚Äôve got this! üôåüèª
author: brookeraybould

For one week only, I will discount it to $30 and include our exact trip itinerary, 1-day park touring plans for all the parks, and free photo editing presets.  Here are my exact timestamps for park opening times at Disney vs. the time you can actually enter‚Ä¶  ANIMAL KINGDOM 8:00 AM - Official Disney Opening Time 6:45 AM - We arrived at AK 7:15 AM - We entered AK 7:30 AM - Rode Avatar Flight of Passage . HOLLYWOOD STUDIOS 9:00 AM - Official Disney Opening Time 7:30 AM - We arrived at HS 8:00 AM - We entered HS 8:15 AM - Rode Rise of the Resistance  MAGIC KINGDOM 9:00 AM - Official Disney Opening Time 7:30 AM - We arrived at MK 7:45 AM - We entered MK 8:20 AM - Rode Seven Dwarfs Mine Train  EPCOT 9:00 AM - Official Disney Opening Time 7:30 AM - We arrived at EPCOT 7:51 AM - We entered EPCOT 8:10 AM - Rode Remy‚Äôs Ratatouille  BOOM! Feels so good. üòÇ  I used to very much dislike Disney - before I understood how it worked, but now I know there is a system - I am fully prepared to dominate it - and our fam loves it! ‚ô•Ô∏è  One of the Disney secret tips we THRIVE on is early park entry. Y‚Äôall know our family is part of the 5AM club (we wake up so early!) - and Disney rewards those who arrive‚Ä¶ EARLY. If you‚Äôre staying at a Disney Resort Hotel, you get access to early park entry. This means that you can begin riding rides 30 minutes before Disney‚Äôs official park opening time. We always get there an hour and a half before the parks open. If you arrive at that time, you‚Äôre almost guaranteed to walk into the park with the first group of people.  So, yes, Disney lets you into the parks way earlier than the ‚Äúofficial‚Äù parking opening time AND even earlier than the early park entry time.   Share any of your Disney tips below!! ‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è

body: For TWO of my favorite systems‚Ä¶  ‚Ä¶. Comment ‚ÄúMORNING‚Äù to learn how to create a morning routine system, and comment ‚ÄúPLAN‚Äù for our family activity and meal calendaring system. üôåüèª  Best-selling author, James Clear, pretty much changed my life when he gave this advice:   ‚Ä¢Winners and losers have the same goals. ‚Ä¢Achieving a goal is only a momentary change. ‚Ä¢Goals restrict your happiness, and ‚Ä¢Goals are at odds with long-term progress.  This is why you should fall in love with SYSTEMS not goals, he says. Systems allow you to win; not goals. Systems aren‚Äôt a ‚Äúmomentary‚Äù win, but are a consistent daily practice that allow you to achieve the results you want, while goals are a once-in-awhile happening. If you aren‚Äôt living the life you want, you probably don‚Äôt need a better goal, but a better system.   Let‚Äôs break these down.   Winners and losers have the same goal: to be successful at ________ (fill in the blank). So, why does one person find success and the other doesn‚Äôt? Clearly, it‚Äôs not the goal that matters, but the system that helps them get there.  Let‚Äôs say your goal is to have a successful laundry system as a mom. One mom finds success in doing the laundry; the other does not. Both moms want a working system, but only one has found success. What is the difference? The mom who finds success has a better system; not a better goal.  Getting to your ‚Äúgoal‚Äù is only a momentary change. Let‚Äôs say you finally get around to doing the laundry after days of letting it slide. The goal of washing, drying, folding, and putting away the laundry has FINALLY been accomplished, but it‚Äôs only momentary. The next day, you‚Äôre going to have to face the same problem. This is why the secret is in the SYSTEM; not the goal.  Goals restrict happiness because they are only once in a while moments in the grand scheme of day to day life. On the other hand, systems are what you are doing consistently NOW in order to get to the goal. Goals are somewhere off in the distance, while systems are in the present moment.  Whenever I find myself in a downward spiral or daydreaming of ‚Äúsomeday‚Äù, instead of focusing on the goal, I ask myself: what is a better system to achieve my goal right now? ‚ô•Ô∏è
author: brookeraybould

body: Comment ‚ÄúDISNEY‚Äù...  ‚Ä¶. To get the UPDATED version of ‚ú®A Mom‚Äôs Guide to Disney World‚ú® PLUS $10 off with code ‚ÄúMAGIC2024‚Äù - valid through midnight July 1st! If you have already purchased, you will receive the updated version!  WHOA. Just when I thought we nailed the Genie+ strategy, Disney goes and pulls Aladdin‚Äôs rug out from under us!!  Guys. This is what makes Disney fun and what I touch upon in my guide. Those who understand the Disney system (and know how to beat the system) ultimately win at the game of Disney (and wait in no lines).  This new Lightning Lane Multi Pass and Single Pass System is no different.  Genie+ has been updated to Lightning Lane Multi Pass, and Individual Lightning Lanes have been updated to Lightning Lane Single Pass. The rides are the SAME in each category with the exception of character meet and greets being removed from lightning lanes altogether. AND, there is a tier system when booking in advance with Lightning Lange Multi Pass.  What is the MAJOR change? Advanced booking.  Lightning Lane Multi Pass and Single Pass can now be booked 7 days in advance of your first resort day if you are a Disney World Resort guest and 3 days in advance of your first park day if you are an off-site guest - both at 7AM EST.  When the clock strikes 7 AM EST (either on your 7 day or 3 day advanced mark), you can then book up to 3 Lightning Lane Multi Pass rides and up to 2 Lightning Lane Single Pass Rides. You must pay for both, but you will be able to see everything BEFORE you book and your return times are locked in until that point.  The catch? There is a tier system with the Lightning Lane Multi Pass advanced booking. Each park has a ‚Äútop tier‚Äù of rides: Magic Kingdom: Peter Pan, Tiana‚Äôs, Space Mountain, Jungle Cruise, Big Thunder. AK: has NO tiers. Hollywood Studios: Slinky Dog, Millenium Falcon, Mickey and Minnie‚Äôs, Rockin‚Äô Rollercoaster. EPCOT: Frozen Ever After, Remy‚Äôs, Soarin‚Äô.  After you book your top tier ride, the next two selections will be out of the remaining former Genie+ rides.  My old Genie+ strategy and early park entry strategy will work PERFECTLY with this new update. Everything will be available in my guide in the next 72 hours!

body: Goodbye low-level decision fatigue; hello planning and organization! üëãüèª Save this post if you find it helpful. ‚úÖ  üëâüèª And, comment the word ‚ÄúPLAN‚Äù and I will send you my customizable planning templates!  My favorite quote from the video is by neuroscientist, Dr. Andrew Huberman. He says: ‚ÄúSpontaneity is great, but life is far easier and everything goes far better when we have protocols, and we adhere to them.‚Äù  With social media, people often question how regimented I am. Sometimes it makes me question myself - am I too‚Ä¶ regimented? It‚Äôs nice to know that one of the world‚Äôs top scientists agrees that while spontaneity is fun every once in awhile, as humans we operate best with routine, planning, and organization. And I‚Äôd argue that so do kids. Of course, we need downtime and free play, but overall structure is a good thing.  Proof: I didn‚Äôt used to plan out our weeks, and our weeks were crazy. But now with four kids, our Sunday weekly planning and meal planning sessions are non-negotiable!  I remember the first time I got the idea to start planning our weeks. As I was scrolling social media, high performance coach Brendon Burchard‚Äôs video stopped me. He said, ‚ÄúIf you do ANYTHING on Sundays, sit down and plan your week ahead.‚Äù  He was referring to business, but I immediately applied it to motherhood. Why are we not planning out our weeks as a family?   That Sunday, Ryan and I sat down (we do this sometimes with the kids; sometimes without), and planned out our week. The week ran SO much smoother, we were kicking ourselves for not having applied this practice sooner.  Low-level decision fatigue is a huge problem for parents. Planning, scheduling, and organization is one way to drastically reduce the amount of decision-making involved in our days.  Send this to a friend, who might benefit and save it for future reference! ‚úÖ
author: brookeraybould

body: Comment ‚ÄúBOOK‚Äù ‚Ä¶ üìö  ‚Ä¶ to get the link to Jocko Willink and Leif Babin‚Äôs book, ‚ÄúExtreme Ownership: How U.S. Navy SEALs Lead and Win.‚Äù Comment ‚ÄúJOB‚Äù to learn how I treat being a mom like a job (free download).  When I first became a mom, it was incredibly joyful, but also very hard. For that reason, I sought out moms who I could RELATE to (friends, social media content, etc.) on the basis of the struggles. Why? Because I wanted to know I wasn‚Äôt alone.  When I saw other moms struggling, it made me feel better.  But, by baby three, I was now four and a half years into motherhood and I had settled in. I knew that motherhood was demanding, but I could also handle it far better. At that point, seeking out what was ‚Äúrelatable‚Äù no longer served me. In fact, it was stagnating me. I no longer needed or wanted to see the mom struggling (bless her heart). What I needed now was an example of a mom, who was thriving.  I not only looked to other moms for inspiration, but I also looked to other high-level professions for inspiration, action steps, and advice. Navy SEALs, professional athletes, business/entrepreneurial leaders, philosophers, high-level thought leaders.  I wanted to find people, who were faced with high-pressure situations on a daily basis and I wanted to see how they THRIVED -  because I wanted to translate those skills to motherhood. How did Serena train? How did Jocko prepare? Literally, what would Jesus do?  And so it goes‚Ä¶  You‚Äôre only as good as the information you seek and the people you surround yourself with. If life isn‚Äôt working out for you, it might be time to change the radio station. üëäüèª‚ô•Ô∏è

body: I have seen this trend and I think it is so wholesome and valuable ü§ç  I feel so many us today lack the community and guidance from the generations before us. Some of my fondest memories are spending time with my grandmas, aunties, and older women in church.   Let‚Äôs share some doubts, questions and wisdom with each other ü§ç  I will start: What is it really like when your children are grown and start to leave home?
author: sarah_wildmothering

body: After having my first born I realised how crucial it is humans rely on each other. For mental, emotional and physical health. I‚Äôm not an independent woman anymore and I‚Äôm going to choose trust over fear, allow my feminine to heal and soften in the arms of a masculine provider.  In a world that encourages independency I choose the opposite üïä  I have been a stay at home mother for 6 years. For the last 6 years I could have been working outside of the home to have my own income just in case anything should happen. I could have missed out on some of the most beautiful six years of my life living in fear that something might happen and I should suddenly need financial independence.  If there is one thing I know about women it‚Äôs how resourceful and resilient we can be and if we had to provide for our families we could figure it out.  At any moment a variety of scenarios COULD happen. I could be employed and get terminated with zero warning leaving me with no income or something could happen that meant I have to completely change my lifestyle from sahm and go out to work.  Growing up the media was blasting how empowering it was to be an independent woman that didn‚Äôt need a man.   But since my first pregnancy I realised how important it is for me to have someone provide and protect so I can fully embrace my role of mother and homemaker üïØ  Over the years I have often been asked about my thoughts in financial dependency so thought I would share here ü§ç  #homemaker #sahm #stayathomewife #homemaking #motherhood #marriage #femininenotfeminist #motherhoodjourney #stayathomemom #stayathomemama
author: sarah_wildmothering

body: Society and the family need strong men.   I see more women online tearing men down than building them up, let‚Äôs change that. Many are in the process of raising sons I can only imagine the effects on them hearing how men are spoken about these days.  Just as we would wish to be spoken to, we can speak of others üïä  #masculinerevival #masculinefeminine #husbandandwife #homemaker #sahm #traditionalwife

body: Quote Elisabeth Elliot, Let me be a woman   Men and woman have always been equal in worth and different by design   The polarity a romance, a dance   Knowing we could likely, unnaturally, do it ourselves but choosing two to become one and allowing the other to meet our needs where our strengths don‚Äôt reside   He carries me and I tend to him   What if we didn‚Äôt need fighting for at all because Gods design is so intricately perfect all along üïØ
author: sarah_wildmothering

body: It‚Äôs often spoken about how expensive it is to be a stay at home mother but for us it is to expensive for me not to be  If I were to work outside of the home my wage would likely just cover the daycare fees. I would much rather live within our means and be home for my family than work for an extra $100 a week.   Running the home is a full time job so I treat it like one üß∫  #homemaker #homemaking #stayathomemum #sahm #stayathomewife #traditionalwife #motherhoodjourney

body: I feared motherhood, I feared how my life would change. I expected the worst.   Why? Because growing up single, unattached women were glorified and motherhood was not   When my first was born I was shocked, I felt like I had been lied to. To think I almost didn‚Äôt become a mother because of all the noise   Starting this page I wanted to shout from the rooftops how beautiful and life altering motherhood is. Suddenly my heart beat outside my body and gave me a greater driving force to enjoy and live life fully more than ever before   We were never ‚Äújust‚Äù mothers. We have the honour of carrying, birthing and raising new life   Motherhood is aspirational, motherhood is so much more than enough, motherhood is a beautiful blessing üïä  #motherhoodisdarling #motherhoodinspired #motherhoodintheraw #motherhoodunplugged #sahm #homemaker #homemaking #wildmotherhood

body: We‚Äôre having a boy!! üíô  I couldn‚Äôt be more excited to share this news. From the beginning of my pregnancy we thought we wouldn‚Äôt find out the gender until the baby arrived. I loved the idea of keeping it a surprise because that‚Äôs what our parents had done for us. But through this pregnancy it was so difficult at the beginning to think about pregnancy without thinking of how hard each day had been because of the sickness. We decided to find out the gender at 25 weeks and it brought us so much joy finding out we are having a little boy.
